          "text": "Here’s what the code is doing and why your scenario behaves that way.\n\n## What happened\n\nYour intuition matches the implementation: **git-ai only “sees” deletions that Git’s status can represent.** For a **never-tracked** file, deleting it is invisible to `git status`: there is no index entry and no working tree file, so **Git emits no line for that path**. Checkpointing is built on that status stream, so there is nothing to turn into a “deletion” checkpoint entry.\n\nThat’s the core reason. There is a second, reinforcing behavior in `get_all_tracked_files`.\n\n## 1. Checkpoints are driven by `git status` output\n\n`get_status_of_files` only keeps paths that appear as `StatusEntry` rows from `repo.status(...)`, and only when they look “changed” (including untracked `?`):\n\n```1078:1097:git-ai/src/commands/checkpoint.rs\n        // Include files that have any change (staged or unstaged) or are untracked\n        let has_change = entry.staged != StatusCode::Unmodified\n            || entry.unstaged != StatusCode::Unmodified\n            || entry.kind == EntryKind::Untracked;\n\n        if has_change {\n            // For deleted files, check if they were text files in HEAD\n            let is_deleted =\n                entry.staged == StatusCode::Deleted || entry.unstaged == StatusCode::Deleted;\n\n            let is_text = if is_deleted {\n                is_text_file_in_head(repo, &entry.path)\n            } else {\n                is_text_file(working_log, &entry.path)\n            };\n```\n\nFor a **tracked** file, deletion shows up as `D` in the XY field, and `is_text_file_in_head` checks the blob at **HEAD**.\n\nFor an **untracked** file you delete: **no row**, so this loop never runs for that path.\n\n## 2. “Deleted + not in Git” is not the same as “tracked deletion”\n\n`is_text_file_in_head` only inspects **HEAD’s tree**. If the path was never committed, it isn’t in HEAD, so even if something tried to treat it as a deletion, this path would not qualify as text via HEAD:\n\n```2091:2122:git-ai/src/commands/checkpoint.rs\nfn is_text_file_in_head(repo: &Repository, path: &str) -> bool {\n    // For deleted files, check if they were text files in HEAD\n    ...\n    match head_tree.get_path(std::path::Path::new(path)) {\n        Ok(entry) => {\n            ...\n        }\n        Err(_) => false,\n    }\n}\n```\n\nSo “deleted untracked temp file” is outside the model used for **deleted** lines in status.\n\n## 3. Paths from older checkpoints are dropped once the file disappears\n\nWhen rebuilding the file set, entries from previous checkpoints are only added if `is_text_file` succeeds **for the path on disk right now** (unless the path is in `dirty_files`):\n\n```1183:1188:git-ai/src/commands/checkpoint.rs\n                if !files.contains(&normalized_path) {\n                    // Check if it's a text file before adding\n                    if is_text_file(working_log, &normalized_path) {\n                        files.insert(normalized_path);\n                    }\n                }\n```\n\nAnd `is_text_file` treats missing files as non-text unless they’re in `dirty_files`:\n\n```2074:2082:git-ai/src/commands/checkpoint.rs\n    if !skip_metadata_check {\n        if let Ok(metadata) = std::fs::metadata(working_log.to_repo_absolute_path(&normalized_path))\n        {\n            if !metadata.is_file() {\n                return false;\n            }\n        } else {\n            return false; // If metadata can't be read, treat as non-text\n        }\n    }\n```\n\nSo after you delete the temp file, that path often **never gets back into** the `files` set passed into `get_status_of_files`, even though an earlier checkpoint mentioned it.\n\n## Summary\n\n| Situation | Visible to `git status`? | Likely in git-ai’s tracked file set after delete? |\n|-----------|--------------------------|---------------------------------------------------|\n| Delete **tracked** file | Yes (`D` in porcelain) | Yes, via