        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Three steps:\n\n**Step 1 — Store your secrets in AWS Secrets Manager**\n\nRun this once per secret (replace the value each time):\n\n```bash\naws secretsmanager create-secret --region us-east-2 \\\n  --name eval********_URL \\\n  --secret-string \"postgresql+asyncpg://postgres.jzquudlqchjaidsuvltt:evalhub2025@aws-1-us-east-2.pooler.supabase.com:6543/postgres\"\n\naws secretsmanager create-secret --region us-east-2 \\\n  --name eval********CRET \\\n  --secret-string \"e1a5********e8b8\"\n\n# repeat for each secret...\n```\n\nAfter each command, AWS returns an ARN like:\n`arn:aws:secretsmanager:us-east-2:123456789012:secret:eval********CdEf`\n\n**Step 2 — Give App Runner permission to read them**\n\nIn the App Runner console → your service → **Configuration** → **Security** → set an **Instance role** that has this IAM policy:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"Effect\": \"Allow\",\n  \"Action\": \"secretsmanager:GetSecretValue\",\n  \"Resource\": \"arn:aws:secretsmanager:us-east-2:YOUR_ACCOUNT_ID:secret:evalhub/*\"\n}\n```\n\n**Step 3 — Reference them in `apprunner.yaml`**\n\nReplace the `env:` entries with a `secrets:` block using the ARNs from Step 1:\n\n```yaml\n  secrets:\n    - name: DATABASE_URL\n      value-from: \"arn:aws:secretsmanager:us-east-2:123456789012:secret:eval********CdEf\"\n    - name: JWT_SECRET\n      value-from: \"arn:aws:secretsmanager:us-east-2:123456789012:secret:eval********ZaBc\"\n    - name: AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID\n      value-from: \"arn:aws:secretsmanager:us-east-2:123456789012:secret:evalhub/AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID-...\"\n    # etc.\n```\n\nApp Runner injects each secret as an environment variable at startup — your app reads them the same way it reads any env var. Nothing sensitive ever lives in the yaml or your git repo.\n\nThe plaintext `env:` and `secrets:` blocks can coexist — non-sensitive values like `AWS_REGION` stay in `env:`, secrets move to `secrets:`.",
