        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Yes, **absolutely do not expose Redis publicly on port 6379.** Redis has no authentication by default and there are automated botnets that constantly scan the internet for open Redis instances. Within hours it will be found and used to execute arbitrary commands on your server (this is a well-known attack vector).\n\n**The right architecture:**\n\nApp Runner → (VPC connector) → EC2 private IP → Redis\n\nBoth App Runner and the EC2 need to be in the same VPC. Then Redis is never exposed to the internet at all.\n\n**Steps:**\n\n1. **In EC2 security group** — remove any inbound rule for port 6379 from `0.0.0.0/0`. Only allow inbound 6379 from within the VPC CIDR (e.g. `10.0.0.0/16`)\n\n2. **Create a VPC connector in App Runner:**\n   - App Runner console → your service → Configuration → **Networking**  \n   - Add a VPC connector pointing to the same VPC/subnets as your EC2\n\n3. **Change `REDIS_URL` to the EC2's private IP** (the `10.x.x.x` address, not the public one):\n\n```yaml\n    - name: REDIS_URL\n      value: \"redis://10.x.x.x:6379/0\"\n```\n\n**Quick mitigation right now while you set this up:** Go to the EC2 security group and remove or restrict inbound port 6379 immediately. App Runner currently can't reach it anyway without a VPC connector, so closing it costs you nothing but prevents attacks.",
