        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Now I have everything I need. Here's your deployment guide for App Runner (API) + EC2 (Celery):\n\n---\n\n## Architecture Overview\n\n```\nFrontend (Vercel)\n       │\n       ▼\nAWS App Runner  ──── Supabase (DB)\n(FastAPI API)   ──── S3 (storage)\n       │\n       ▼ (shared Redis)\nElastiCache Serverless Redis\n       ▲\n       │\n  EC2 Instance\n(Celery Workers)\n```\n\nBoth App Runner and EC2 use the **same Docker image** from ECR — Celery just overrides the `CMD`.\n\n---\n\n## Step 1: Push the Image to ECR\n\n```bash\n# Create the ECR repo\naws ecr create-repository --repository-name evalhub-backend --region us-east-2\n\n# Authenticate Docker to ECR\naws ecr get-login-password --region us-east-2 \\\n  | docker login --username AWS \\\n    --password-stdin <ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com\n\n# Build (this takes a while — it clones lighteval)\ncd backend\ndocker build -t evalhub-backend .\n\n# Tag and push\ndocker tag evalhub-backend:latest \\\n  <ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest\ndocker push <ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step 2: Set Up Redis (ElastiCache Serverless)\n\n1. Go to **ElastiCache → Serverless caches → Create**.\n2. Name: `evalhub-redis`, Engine: Redis.\n3. Note the endpoint — it looks like `evalhub-redis.abc123.serverless.use2.cache.amazonaws.com:6379`.\n4. **Important:** ElastiCache lives in a VPC. You'll need VPC connectors for App Runner and your EC2 in the same VPC.\n\n> **Simpler alternative:** Run Redis on the EC2 instance alongside Celery (`redis-server`), then use the EC2's private IP as `REDIS_URL`. Skip the VPC connector for App Runner by opening port 6379 on the EC2's security group to App Runner's egress IP. Less reliable but zero extra cost.\n\n---\n\n## Step 3: Store Secrets in AWS Secrets Manager\n\nCreate one secret named `evalhub/backend` with all env vars:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"DATABASE_URL\": \"postgresql+asyncpg://...\",\n  \"SUPABASE_URL\": \"https://...\",\n  \"SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY\": \"...\",\n  \"SUPABASE_SECRET_KEY\": \"...\",\n  \"SUPABASE_JWT_SECRET\": \"...\",\n  \"AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID\": \"...\",\n  \"AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY\": \"...\",\n  \"AWS_REGION\": \"us-east-2\",\n  \"S3_BUCKET_NAME\": \"evalhub-bucket\",\n  \"REDIS_URL\": \"redis://evalhub-redis...6379/0\",\n  \"HF_TOKEN\": \"hf_...\"\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step 4: Deploy the API on App Runner\n\n1. Go to **App Runner → Create service**.\n2. Source: **Container registry → Amazon ECR → Browse** → select `evalhub-backend:latest`.\n3. Deployment trigger: **Automatic** (redeploys when you push to ECR).\n4. **Configure service:**\n   - Port: `8000`\n   - CPU: `1 vCPU`, Memory: `2 GB` (FastAPI is lightweight)\n   - Environment variables: add each key from Secrets Manager, or use the Secrets Manager ARN injection.\n5. **Health check:** Path `/api/health`, protocol HTTP.\n6. If using ElastiCache (VPC): Add a **VPC connector** pointing to the same VPC/subnets as ElastiCache, with a security group that allows outbound 6379.\n7. Deploy and copy the App Runner URL (e.g. `https://abc123.us-east-2.awsapprunner.com`).\n\n---\n\n## Step 5: Launch EC2 for Celery\n\nEval tasks run ML workloads with up to 1-hour timeouts — use at least a **`c5.xlarge`** (4 vCPU, 8 GB).\n\n**Launch an EC2 instance:**\n- AMI: Amazon Linux 2023\n- Instance type: `c5.xlarge` (or `c5.2xlarge` if running large model evals)\n- VPC: same as ElastiCache if using that\n- Security group: allow SSH (22) inbound from your IP; allow 6379 outbound to Redis\n\n**Bootstrap the instance (run on EC2 via SSH):**\n\n```bash\n# Install Docker\nsudo dnf install docker -y\nsudo systemctl start docker\nsudo systemctl enable docker\nsudo usermod -aG docker ec2-user\n\n# Install AWS CLI (for ECR auth)\nsudo dnf install awscli -y\n\n# Authenticate to ECR (attach an IAM role with ECR read access to the instance instead)\naws ecr get-login-password --region us-east-2 \\\n  | docker login --username AWS \\\n    --password-stdin <ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com\n\n# Pull the image\ndocker pull <ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest\n```\n\n**Run the Celery worker:**\n\n```bash\ndocker run -d \\\n  --name celery-worker \\\n  --restart unless-stopped \\\n  -e DATABASE_URL=\"postgresql+asyncpg://...\" \\\n  -e REDIS_URL=\"redis://...\" \\\n  -e SUPABASE_URL=\"...\" \\\n  -e SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=\"...\" \\\n  -e SUPABASE_SECRET_KEY=\"...\" \\\n  -e SUPABASE_JWT_SECRET=\"...\" \\\n  -e AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=\"...\" \\\n  -e AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=\"...\" \\\n  -e AWS_REGION=\"us-east-2\" \\\n  -e S3_BUCKET_NAME=\"evalhub-bucket\" \\\n  -e HF_TOKEN=\"hf_...\" \\\n  <ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest \\\n  celery -A api.core.celery_app:celery_app worker \\\n    --loglevel=info --pool=solo --concurrency=1\n```\n\n> Use `--concurrency=1 --pool=solo` since each eval task is long-running and CPU-heavy. Run multiple containers for parallelism rather than multiple Celery threads.\n\n**To update the worker when you push a new image:**\n\n```bash\ndocker pull <ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest\ndocker stop celery-worker && docker rm celery-worker\n# re-run the docker run command above\n```\n\n---\n\n## Step 6: Update the Frontend\n\nUpdate `vercel.json` to point at your App Runner URL:\n\n```json\n\"destination\": \"https://abc123.us-east-2.awsapprunner.com/api/:path*\"\n```\n\nAnd update `frontend/.env`:\n\n```\nVITE_API_URL=https://abc123.us-east-2.awsapprunner.com\n```\n\n---\n\n## IAM Permissions Needed\n\n| Resource | Needs |\n|---|---|\n| EC2 instance role | `ecr:GetAuthorizationToken`, `ecr:BatchGetImage`, `ecr:GetDownloadUrlForLayer` |\n| App Runner instance role | Same ECR perms + `secretsmanager:GetSecretValue` if using Secrets Manager injection |\n| Celery worker (via env vars) | `s3:*` on `evalhub-bucket` (already in your AWS creds) |\n\n---\n\n## Estimated Monthly Cost (dev-sized)\n\n| Service | Cost |\n|---|---|\n| App Runner (1 vCPU / 2 GB, ~50% active) | ~$25–40 |\n| EC2 `c5.xlarge` (on-demand) | ~$122 |\n| ElastiCache Serverless Redis (light usage) | ~$10–20 |\n| ECR storage | ~$1 |\n| **Total** | **~$160–180/mo** |\n\nUse a **Spot instance** for EC2 to cut the Celery machine cost by ~70% (~$36/mo) — Celery can re-queue tasks if the instance is interrupted since you have `task_acks_late=True` and `task_reject_on_worker_lost=True` already configured.",
