          "text": "Here are the full steps:\n\n## 1. Get Your AWS Account ID\n```bash\naws configure list  # confirm credentials are set up\naws sts get-caller-identity --query Account --output text\n```\nSave the account ID — you'll use it as `<ACCOUNT_ID>` below.\n\n## 2. Create the ECR Repository\n```bash\naws ecr create-repository \\\n  --repository-name evalhub-backend \\\n  --region us-east-2\n```\n\n## 3. Build & Push the Image\n```bash\ncd /Users/Andrew/School/CPEN_491_Baseten/evalhub/backend\n\n# Login to ECR\naws ecr get-login-password --region us-east-2 \\\n  | docker login --username AWS \\\n    --password-stdin <ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com\n\n# Build (this will take ~5-10 min due to lighteval clone)\ndocker build -t evalhub-backend .\n\n# Tag and push\ndocker tag evalhub-backend:latest \\\n  <ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest\n\ndocker push \\\n  <ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest\n```\n\n## 4. Create App Runner Service\n\nIn the AWS console:\n1. **App Runner → Create service**\n2. Source: **Container registry → Amazon ECR**\n3. Image URI: `<ACCOUNT_ID>.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest`\n4. Deployment trigger: **Manual** (you'll push + redeploy manually)\n5. ECR access role: create new (App Runner needs permission to pull from ECR)\n6. Port: `8000`\n7. CPU: `1 vCPU`, Memory: `2 GB`\n8. Health check path: `/api/health`\n\n## 5. Set Environment Variables in App Runner\n\nUnder **Environment variables**, add everything from your `.env`:\n\n| Key | Value |\n|---|---|\n| `DATABASE_URL` | your Supabase URL |\n| `SUPABASE_URL` | ... |\n| `SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY` | ... |\n| `SUPABASE_SECRET_KEY` | ... |\n| `SUPABASE_JWT_SECRET` | ... |\n| `AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID` | ... |\n| `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY` | ... |\n| `AWS_REGION` | `us-east-2` |\n| `S3_BUCKET_NAME` | `evalhub-bucket` |\n| `HF_TOKEN` | ... |\n| `REDIS_URL` | ⚠️ see note below |\n\n> **Important:** `REDIS_URL` is currently `redis://localhost:6379/0` which won't work in App Runner. You need a real Redis before the API can fully function. Options: ElastiCache, or Redis running on your EC2 instance (use its public/private IP). Come back to this after setting up EC2.",
