        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "The connection between App Runner and Celery is entirely through **Redis** — the API enqueues tasks to Redis, Celery picks them up. Here's the full setup:\n\n## 1. Launch an EC2 Instance\n\nIn AWS console → EC2 → Launch instance:\n- **AMI:** Amazon Linux 2023\n- **Instance type:** `c5.xlarge` (eval tasks are CPU-heavy)\n- **Key pair:** create or select one (you need SSH access)\n- **Security group — add these inbound rules:**\n  - SSH (22) from your IP\n  - Custom TCP **6379** from anywhere (or scope to App Runner's egress IPs later)\n- **Storage:** 30 GB minimum (lighteval image is large)\n\n## 2. SSH In and Install Docker\n\n```bash\nssh -i your-key.pem ec2-user@<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>\n\nsudo dnf install docker -y\nsudo systemctl start docker\nsudo systemctl enable docker\nsudo usermod -aG docker ec2-user\n# Reconnect SSH for group to take effect\nexit\nssh -i your-key.pem ec2-user@<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>\n```\n\n## 3. Start Redis on EC2\n\n```bash\ndocker run -d \\\n  --name redis \\\n  --restart unless-stopped \\\n  -p 6379:6379 \\\n  redis:7-alpine\n```\n\n## 4. Authenticate to ECR and Pull the Image\n\n```bash\nsudo dnf install awscli -y\n\naws configure\n# Enter your AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID, AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY, region: us-east-2\n\naws ecr get-login-password --region us-east-2 \\\n  | docker login --username AWS \\\n    --password-stdin 214863335048.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com\n\ndocker pull 214863335048.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest\n```\n\n## 5. Run the Celery Worker\n\n```bash\ndocker run -d \\\n  --name celery-worker \\\n  --restart unless-stopped \\\n  -e DATABASE_URL=\"postgresql+asyncpg://postgres.jzquudlqchjaidsuvltt:evalhub2025@aws-1-us-east-2.pooler.supabase.com:6543/postgres\" \\\n  -e REDIS_URL=\"redis://localhost:6379/0\" \\\n  -e SUPABASE_URL=\"https://jzquudlqchjaidsuvltt.supabase.co\" \\\n  -e SUPABASE_PUBLISHABLE_KEY=\"...\" \\\n  -e SUPABASE_SECRET_KEY=\"...\" \\\n  -e SUPABASE_JWT_SECRET=\"...\" \\\n  -e AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID=\"...\" \\\n  -e AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=\"...\" \\\n  -e AWS_REGION=\"us-east-2\" \\\n  -e S3_BUCKET_NAME=\"evalhub-bucket\" \\\n  -e HF_TOKEN=\"hf_R********QDrj\" \\\n  --network host \\\n  214863335048.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest \\\n  celery -A api.core.celery_app:celery_app worker \\\n    --loglevel=info --pool=solo --concurrency=1\n```\n\n> `--network host` lets the container reach Redis on `localhost:6379`.\n\n## 6. Connect App Runner to This Redis\n\nGo to App Runner → your service → **Configuration → Environment variables** and update:\n\n```\nREDIS_URL = redis://<EC2_PUBLIC_IP>:6379/0\n```\n\nThen **redeploy** the App Runner service. Now the API will enqueue tasks to Redis on EC2, and Celery will pick them up.\n\n## 7. Verify It's Working\n\n```bash\n# On EC2, watch Celery logs\ndocker logs -f celery-worker\n```\n\nSubmit an eval from the frontend — you should see the task appear in the Celery logs.\n\n---\n\n**Optional: Assign an Elastic IP to EC2** so the public IP doesn't change on instance restarts (otherwise you'd need to update `REDIS_URL` in App Runner every time).",
