          "text": "For more concurrent tasks, you have two options:\n\n**Option A: Multiple containers on the same EC2 (easiest)**\n\n```bash\nfor i in 2 3 4; do\n  docker run -d \\\n    --name celery-worker-$i \\\n    --restart unless-stopped \\\n    --env-file .env \\\n    --network host \\\n    214863335048.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest \\\n    celery -A api.core.celery_app:celery_app worker \\\n      --loglevel=info --pool=solo --concurrency=1\ndone\n```\n\nThis gives you 4 total workers (worker 1 + workers 2, 3, 4).\n\n**BUT** — eval tasks are CPU-heavy. A `c5.xlarge` has 4 vCPUs, so **4 workers max** makes sense. Running more than your vCPU count will cause them to fight over CPU and everything slows down.\n\nIf you want more than 4 concurrent evals, you'd need a bigger instance (`c5.2xlarge` = 8 vCPU, `c5.4xlarge` = 16 vCPU) or multiple EC2 instances.\n\n**What instance type did you launch?** That determines how many workers you should run.",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:16:05.382Z",
          "id": "efd13b16-2db3-4d23-b469-a098fb2834ff"
        },
        {
          "type": "user",
          "text": "why not set pool to more",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:16:24.968Z",
          "id": "f9c902e7-7478-4bfb-a8da-86b368e42daa"
        },
        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Because `--pool=solo` **ignores** the concurrency setting entirely — it's a fundamentally single-threaded pool with no worker processes. Setting `--concurrency=4` with `--pool=solo` still runs 1 task at a time.\n\nTo use concurrency properly you'd switch to `--pool=prefork` (the default):\n\n```bash\ncelery -A api.core.celery_app:celery_app worker \\\n  --loglevel=info --pool=prefork --concurrency=4\n```\n\n**But the reason `solo` was chosen** is that eval tasks likely spawn subprocesses themselves (lighteval, transformers, etc.). When Celery's prefork pool forks child processes that then spawn their own children, you get issues with:\n- CUDA/GPU context sharing\n- Multiprocessing conflicts in PyTorch/HuggingFace\n- File descriptor leaks\n\n`solo` avoids all of that by keeping everything in one process.\n\n**So the right approach for parallelism is multiple containers** (each running `--pool=solo`), not increasing concurrency within one container. Each container is fully isolated with its own process tree.",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:16:26.943Z",
          "id": "c372385f-15de-4616-b48d-abb86cf742a8"
        },
        {
          "type": "user",
          "text": "what is the existing dockerfile",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:16:52.911Z",
          "id": "56290c61-1db9-4e95-9306-d9f48ab7cdac"
        },
        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Here's what it does:\n\n```55:55:backend/Dockerfile\nCMD [\"python\", \"-m\", \"api\"]\n```\n\nThe full Dockerfile:\n\n```1:55:backend/Dockerfile\n# syntax=docker/dockerfile:1\nFROM python:3.12-slim AS base\n\n# Set environment variables\nENV PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE=1 \\\n    PYTH********ERED=1 \\\n    PYTH********DLER=1 \\\n    PIP_NO_CACHE_DIR=1 \\\n    PIP_DISABLE_PIP_VERSION_CHECK=1\n\n# Install system dependencies\nRUN apt-get update && apt-get install -y --no-install-recommends \\\n    curl \\\n    build-essential \\\n    git \\\n    libpq-dev \\\n    libffi-dev \\\n    && rm -rf /var/lib/apt/lists/*\n\n# Install Poetry\nENV POETRY_HOME=\"/opt/poetry\" \\\n    POETRY_VIRTUALENVS_CREATE=false \\\n    POETRY_NO_INTERACTION=1\nRUN curl -sSL https://install.python-poetry.org | python3 -\nENV PATH=\"$POET********/bin:$PATH\"\n\nWORKDIR /app\n\n# Copy dependency files first for better caching\nCOPY pyproject.toml poetry.lock ./\n\n# Copy application code\nCOPY . .\n\n# Install all dependencies (--no-root skips installing the project itself)\nRUN poetry install --no-interaction",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:16:56.199Z",
          "id": "4f8440cd-d759-44fb-ba4c-af7444c81618"
        },
        {
          "type": "user",
          "text": "what does the existing code do for pool for celery?",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:17:14.035Z",
          "id": "11af92cf-ffc0-4997-becc-db5933348449"
        },
        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "No pool is configured in the code — it uses Celery's default, which is **prefork**. The `--pool=solo` flag was only in the `docker-compose.yml` command override.\n\nSo the code itself has no opinion on the pool. It's whatever you pass on the CLI when starting the worker. `worker_prefetch_multiplier=1` just means each worker only fetches one task at a time (no pre-fetching ahead), which pairs well with long-running tasks regardless of pool type.",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:17:18.941Z",
          "id": "2b0be7f4-422a-4240-b301-2b082590f96e"
        },
        {
          "type": "user",
          "text": "dont set the pool. let workers be larger.",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:19:30.750Z",
          "id": "59a6c700-e937-4e97-abf8-8e7a6068339a"
        },
        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Then just drop `--pool=solo` from the command and set `--concurrency` to match your vCPUs:\n\n```bash\ndocker run -d \\\n  --name celery-worker \\\n  --restart unless-stopped \\\n  --env-file .env \\\n  --network host \\\n  214863335048.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest \\\n  celery -A api.core.celery_app:celery_app worker \\\n    --loglevel=info --concurrency=4\n```\n\nThis uses prefork (default) with 4 concurrent tasks. Set `--concurrency` to however many vCPUs your EC2 instance has. What instance type did you pick?",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:19:35.183Z",
          "id": "831a7ed8-a85d-4822-ae8b-e907a5673e15"
        },
        {
          "type": "user",
          "text": "@/Users/Andrew/.cursor/projects/Users-Andrew-School-CPEN-491-Baseten-evalhub/terminals/6.txt:315-375",
