          "id": "4547122f-dc3b-4f03-b5a8-05795e3488a8"
        },
        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "The prefork workers are getting OOM-killed (SIGKILL) — not enough memory on the instance. Each prefork worker loads the full app including all the ML imports, so 4 workers × heavy deps = out of memory.\n\nGo back to `--pool=solo`:\n\n```bash\ndocker stop celery-worker && docker rm celery-worker\n\ndocker run -d \\\n  --name celery-worker \\\n  --restart unless-stopped \\\n  --env-file .env \\\n  --network host \\\n  214863335048.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/evalhub-backend:latest \\\n  celery -A api.core.celery_app:celery_app worker \\\n    --loglevel=info --pool=solo\n```\n\nThis is exactly why `docker-compose.yml` used `--pool=solo` — the ML imports alone eat most of the RAM, so you can't fork multiple processes.\n\nIf you want more parallelism, you need a bigger instance (more RAM, not more vCPUs). What instance type are you on? Run on EC2:\n\n```bash\ncurl -s http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/instance-type\n```",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:29:05.227Z",
          "id": "d8c6758a-cf2b-408a-814a-147c533536f0"
        },
        {
          "type": "user",
          "text": "on micro right now",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:31:15.813Z",
          "id": "8b14dd63-96c9-4b6c-9d36-f6413e1f6877"
        },
        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "That's the problem — `t2.micro` / `t3.micro` only has **1 GB RAM**. The ML dependencies (transformers, lighteval, etc.) alone eat most of that just on import.\n\n`--pool=solo` will work on micro for now (1 task at a time, minimal memory), but for actual eval runs you'll likely hit OOM during task execution too.\n\nYou should upgrade the instance. Recommended minimum for eval workloads:\n\n| Instance | vCPU | RAM | Cost/mo |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| `t3.medium` | 2 | 4 GB | ~$30 |\n| `t3.large` | 2 | 8 GB | ~$60 |\n| `c5.xlarge` | 4 | 8 GB | ~$122 |\n| `c5.2xlarge` | 8 | 16 GB | ~$245 |\n\nTo upgrade without losing your setup:\n1. **Stop** the instance in EC2 console\n2. **Actions → Instance settings → Change instance type**\n3. Select `t3.large` or `c5.xlarge`\n4. **Start** the instance\n\nYour `.env`, Docker images, and containers won't survive a stop/start as-is — you'll need to re-run the Celery container after restart. But the instance storage (EBS) persists, so your pulled images stay cached.",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T03:31:18.972Z",
          "id": "cf697910-55dd-40e3-a0c7-6217b09782f3"
        },
        {
