          "text": "what steps to redo after the restart",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-04T04:00:21.088Z",
          "id": "5f7e1dd0-050f-4792-9a24-25579f07aec2"
        },
        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "After the instance restarts with the new instance type, SSH back in and run:\n\n**1. Start Redis**\n```bash\ndocker start redis\n```\n\n**2. Re-authenticate to ECR** (auth token expires)\n```bash\naws ecr get-login-password --region us-east-2 \\\n  | docker login --username AWS \\\n    --password-stdin 214863335048.dkr.ecr.us-east-2.amazonaws.com\n```\n\n**3. Start the Celery worker**\n```bash\ndocker start celery-worker\n```\n\n> Since you used `--restart unless-stopped`, Docker will actually try to restart the containers automatically on boot — but only if the Docker daemon itself starts on boot. Check if that's configured:\n\n```bash\nsudo systemctl is-enabled docker\n```\n\nIf it says `enabled`, Redis and Celery will restart automatically on reboot and you don't need to do steps 1 or 3 manually. You'd only need step 2 if the ECR token is needed (it's only needed for `docker pull`, not for running already-pulled images).\n\n**TL;DR:** If Docker is enabled as a service, just SSH in and verify with `docker ps` — everything should already be running.",
