          "text": "Here is a concise picture of how git-ai behaves and what can explain a missing authorship note on a huge commit.\n\n## 1. Failures are easy to miss: post-commit errors do not fail the commit\n\n`handle_rewrite_log_event` always appends the rewrite event, then runs authorship work. If `post_commit` fails, the error is **logged only**; the commit is already done and nothing is surfaced as a hard failure:\n\n```1231:1264:/Users/Andrew/School/ReSeSS_Research/tool_testing/git-ai/src/git/repository.rs\n    pub fn handle_rewrite_log_event(\n        &mut self,\n        rewrite_log_event: RewriteLogEvent,\n        commit_author: String,\n        supress_output: bool,\n        apply_side_effects: bool,\n    ) {\n        let log = self\n            .storage\n            .append_rewrite_event(rewrite_log_event.clone())\n            .expect(\"Error writing .git/ai/rewrite_log\");\n\n        if apply_side_effects\n            && let Err(error) = rewrite_authorship_if_needed(\n                self,\n                &rewrite_log_event,\n                commit_author,\n                &log,\n                supress_output,\n            )\n        {\n            debug_log(&format!(\n                \"rewrite_authorship_if_needed failed for {:?}: {}\",\n                rewrite_log_event, error\n            ));\n            crate::observability::log_error(\n                &error,\n                Some(serde_json::json!({\n                    \"component\": \"repository\",\n                    \"operation\": \"handle_rewrite_log_event\",\n                    \"rewrite_event\": rewrite_log_event,\n                })),\n            );\n        }\n    }\n```\n\nSo any OOM, timeout, subprocess error, or serialization error in `post_commit` yields **no note** while the commit stays on `HEAD`.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Git notes and “size”\n\nNotes are normal git objects (blobs) written via stdin, so you are not limited by argv length:\n\n```13:30:/Users/Andrew/School/ReSeSS_Research/tool_testing/git-ai/src/git/refs.rs\npub fn notes_add(\n    repo: &Repository,\n    commit_sha: &str,\n    note_content: &str,\n) -> Result<(), GitAiError> {\n    let mut args = repo.global_args_for_exec();\n    args.push(\"notes\".to_string());\n    args.push(\"--ref=ai\".to_string());\n    args.push(\"add\".to_string());\n    args.push(\"-f\".to_string()); // Always force overwrite\n    args.push(\"-F\".to_string());\n    args.push(\"-\".to_string()); // Read note content from stdin\n    args.push(commit_sha.to_string());\n\n    // Use stdin to provide the note content to avoid command line length limits\n    exec_git_stdin(&args, note_content.as_bytes())?;\n```\n\nThere is no small fixed “note size” cap in this path. Practical limits are **memory** (building `note_content` as one `String` in Rust) and **git**’s ability to store a very large blob, not “notes are too small.”\n\n---\n\n## 3. Where scale *does* hurt in git-ai (more than note storage)\n\n### A. Many pathspecs (>1000): full `git diff`, then filter\n\nIf more than `MAX_PATHSPEC_ARGS` (1000) paths are in the set, `diff_added_lines` does **not** pass them on the command line; it runs a **full** diff and filters in memory:\n\n```2171:2214:/Users/Andrew/School/ReSeSS_Research/tool_testing/git-ai/src/git/repository.rs\n    pub fn diff_added_lines(\n        &self,\n        from_ref: &str,\n        to_ref: &str,\n        pathspecs: Option<&HashSet<String>>,\n    ) -> Result<HashMap<String, Vec<u32>>, GitAiError> {\n        // ...\n        let needs_post_filter = if let Some(paths) = pathspecs {\n            if paths.is_empty() {\n                return Ok(HashMap::new());\n            }\n            if paths.len() > MAX_PATHSPEC_ARGS {\n                true\n            } else {\n                args.push(\"--\".to_string());\n                for path in paths {\n                    args.push(path.clone());\n                }\n                false\n            }\n        } else {\n            false\n        };\n\n        let output = exec_git_with_profile(&args, InternalGitProfile::PatchParse)?;\n        let diff_output = String::from_utf8_lossy(&output.stdout);\n\n        let mut result = parse_diff_added_lines(&diff_output)?;\n\n        if needs_post_filter && let Some(paths) = pathspecs {\n            result.retain(|path, _| paths.contains(path));\n        }\n\n        Ok(result)\n    }\n```\n\n`MAX_PATHSPEC_ARGS` is 1000 (`git-ai/src/git/status.rs`). For a “massive” commit touching **>1000 paths** that git-ai cares about, this loads the **entire** unified diff into a string. Even with `-U0`, that can be enormous (every added line still appears as a `+` line). That can exhaust memory, make `git diff` very slow, or cause the subprocess to fail—any of which becomes a **silent** post-commit failure as in §1.\n\n### B. Huge JSON for the note itself: `change_history` + line contents\n\n`post_commit` builds `change_history` from **every** checkpoint, including per-file `added_line_contents` / `deleted_line_contents` (full line text), not just ranges:\n\n```186:236:/Users/Andrew/School/ReSeSS_Research/tool_testing/git-ai/src/authorship/post_commit.rs\n    let change_history: Vec<crate::authorship::authorship_log_serialization::ChangeHistoryEntry> =\n        parent_working_log\n            .iter()\n            .map(|cp| {\n                // ...\n                let mut files = std::collections::BTreeMap::new();\n                for entry in &cp.entries {\n                    // ...\n                    files.insert(\n                        entry.file.clone(),\n                        FileChangeDetail {\n                            added_lines: fmt(\n                                entry.added_line_ranges.as_deref().unwrap_or(&[]),\n                            ),\n                            deleted_lines: fmt(\n                                entry.deleted_line_ranges.as_deref().unwrap_or(&[]),\n                            ),\n                            added_line_contents: fmt_entries(\n                                entry.added_line_entries.as_deref().unwrap_or(&[]),\n                            ),\n                            deleted_line_contents: fmt_entries(\n                                entry.deleted_line_entries.as_deref().unwrap_or(&[]),\n                            ),\n                        },\n                    );\n                }\n```\n\nMany checkpoints × many files × large snippets can make `serialize_to_string()` very large and memory-heavy **before** `notes_add` runs.\n\n### C. Expensive stats are skipped on large commits—but notes are not\n\nThe `STATS_SKIP_*` constants only skip **terminal stats / metrics**, not writing the note:\n\n```19:25:/Users/Andrew/School/ReSeSS_Research/tool_testing/git-ai/src/authorship/post_commit.rs\n/// Skip expensive post-commit stats when this threshold is exceeded.\nconst STATS_SKIP_MAX_HUNKS: usize = 1000;\nconst STATS_SKIP_MAX_ADDED_LINES: usize = 6000;\nconst STATS_SKIP_MAX_FILES_WITH_ADDITIONS: usize = 200;\n```\n\nSo “stats were skipped” does not explain a missing note; it only explains missing pretty stats.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Direct answers to your questions\n\n| Question | Short answer |\n|----------|----------------|\n| **Anything in git-ai that could “break” so no log is written?** | Yes: **any** `Err` from `post_commit` is caught in `handle_rewrite_log_event` and does not undo the commit. |\n| **Is size the issue?** | **Plausible**, especially (1) **>1000 pathspecs** → full diff in memory, (2) **huge serialized note** from checkpoints + `change_history` + prompts, (3) **RAM** while holding diff + JSON + blobs. |\n| **Git notes size?** | Notes are blob contents; stdin avoids CLI limits. The bottleneck is usually **building/holding** that blob in the git-ai process, not a special “notes quota.” |\n| **Lots of checkpoints / attributions?** | Yes: more data in working log → larger `change_history` and metadata → bigger allocation and serialization cost. |\n\n---\n\n## 5. What to check on that commit\n\n1. **How the commit was created** — `git commit --no-verify` skips hooks, so **no** git-ai post-commit (and no note).  \n2. **Whether git-ai’s post-commit actually ran** — look for `rewrite_authorship_if_needed failed` / `handle_rewrite_log_event` in debug or observability logs.  \n3. **Path and checkpoint count** — if the working log for the parent had **>1000** relevant paths, you hit the full-diff path above.  \n4. **Parent / working log** — if something went wrong earlier (e.g. working log for wrong base), you could get errors before `notes_add`; still swallowed the same way.\n\nI can’t see your repo’s `.git/ai` logs from here; if you paste the relevant log lines around that SHA or confirm path/checkpoint counts, we can narrow it further.",
