          "text": "**Generally no** — git-ai does not rely on `.gitignore` for this. It applies its **own** ignore list, and that list always includes `node_modules`.\n\nBuilt-in defaults include:\n\n```6:27:/Users/Andrew/School/ReSeSS_Research/tool_testing/git-ai/src/authorship/ignore.rs\nconst DEFAULT_IGNORE_PATTERNS: &[&str] = &[\n    \"*.lock\",\n    \"Cargo.lock\",\n    // ...\n    \"**/vendor/**\",\n    \"**/node_modules/**\",\n    \"**/__snapshots__/**\",\n    // ...\n];\n```\n\nCheckpoints merge those defaults with `.gitattributes` (linguist-generated), `.git-ai-ignore`, and any extra patterns via `effective_ignore_patterns`, then filter paths with `should_ignore_file_with_matcher` (for example in `get_all_tracked_files` when gathering files to checkpoint).\n\nSo **leaving `node_modules` out of `.gitignore` does not make git-ai start checkpointing under `node_modules`**, as long as the path matches the default glob (normal `.../node_modules/...` layouts).\n\n**Edge cases:** If a path is weird enough that it doesn’t match `**/node_modules/**`, or you customize ignores in a way that drops that behavior, behavior could differ. The test suite explicitly checks that default patterns exclude things like `Cargo.lock` even when present; the same mechanism applies to `node_modules`.\n\n**Summary:** For typical repos, **no** — `node_modules` is excluded from checkpoint processing by git-ai’s defaults, independent of `.gitignore`. (You should still ignore it in git so Git itself doesn’t track it.)",
