        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "It depends how you measure “1 MB” and the encoding.\n\n**Bytes on disk (what `ls -l` / `wc -c` show)**\n\n- **1 MiB (1024×1024 bytes)** — common on Unix/macOS  \n  - Plain ASCII (1 byte per character): **1,048,576 characters = exactly 1 MiB**  \n  - To **exceed** 1 MiB: **1,048,577** characters (or bytes) or more  \n\n- **1 MB (1,000,000 bytes)** — SI “decimal” megabyte  \n  - ASCII: **1,000,000 characters = 1 MB**  \n  - To **exceed** 1 MB: **1,000,001** characters or more  \n\n**Characters vs bytes**\n\n- **ASCII-only** (letters, digits, `\\n`, space): **1 character ≈ 1 byte** in UTF-8.  \n- **Non-ASCII** (many emoji, some symbols): one “character” can be **several bytes**, so you need **fewer characters** to reach the same file size.\n\n**Practical answer for a `.txt` of normal English/ASCII**\n\nUse **1,048,577** bytes (or characters) to be just over **1 MiB**, or **1,000,001** to be just over **1 MB** in the decimal sense.",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-03T00:17:46.854Z",
