        },
        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Here’s what the **git-ai** code actually does at checkpoint time.\n\n## It does not “untrack” anything in Git\n\nCheckpoint logic does **not** run `git rm --cached`, change the index, or stop Git from tracking a path. It only decides **which paths go into the working log / checkpoint attribution** (and related processing). Your question about “remove from tracking” is **no** in the usual Git sense.\n\n## How `.gitignore` and ignored files interact\n\nIn `get_status_of_files`, entries with **`EntryKind::Ignored`** are skipped (Git’s “ignored” path, e.g. untracked paths that match ignore rules):\n\n```1063:1071:/Users/Andrew/School/ReSeSS_Research/tool_testing/git-ai/src/commands/checkpoint.rs\n    for entry in statuses {\n        // Skip ignored files\n        if entry.kind == EntryKind::Ignored {\n            continue;\n        }\n\n        if should_ignore_file_with_matcher(&entry.path, ignore_matcher) {\n            continue;\n        }\n```\n\nSo **untracked** files that Git considers ignored (including typical `.env` in `.gitignore`) are **not** pulled into this checkpoint file list.\n\n**Tracked** files are different: if `.env` is already in the repo, Git normally still reports it as an ordinary tracked change, **not** as `Ignored`, so it can still be included in checkpoint processing when it changes.\n\n## What “ignore” means for git-ai (not the whole `.gitignore` file)\n\nCheckpoint builds an ignore matcher from **`effective_ignore_patterns`**: built-in defaults (locks, `node_modules`, etc.), **`.git-ai-ignore`**, linguist-generated patterns from `.gitattributes`, and optional user/extra patterns — **not** a full merge of `.gitignore`:\n\n```188:201:/Users/Andrew/School/ReSeSS_Research/tool_testing/git-ai/src/authorship/ignore.rs\npub fn effective_ignore_patterns(\n    repo: &Repository,\n    user_patterns: &[String],\n    extra_patterns: &[String],\n) -> Vec<String> {\n    let mut patterns = default_ignore_patterns();\n    patterns.extend(load_linguist_generated_patterns_from_root_gitattributes(\n        repo,\n    ));\n    patterns.extend(load_git_ai_ignore_patterns(repo));\n    patterns.extend(extra_patterns.iter().cloned());\n    patterns.extend(user_patterns.iter().cloned());\n    dedupe_patterns(patterns)\n}\n```\n\n`.env` is **not** in the default pattern list; to always exclude it from git-ai’s matcher you’d rely on **`.git-ai-ignore`** (or those other pattern sources), in addition to Git’s own ignored status for untracked files.\n\n**Summary:** At checkpoint time, git-ai **skips** ignored/untracked paths (and paths matching its own effective patterns). It does **not** remove `.env` or anything else from **Git tracking**. Tracked `.env` can still be included when it changes unless you also exclude it via mechanisms above.",
