          "id": "38a33ba1-6918-4063-9c8e-76fbd10e2ec4"
        },
        {
          "type": "user",
          "text": "what does git ignore? Are you sure it ignores all files in gitignore?",
          "timestamp": "2026-04-02T23:49:52.950Z",
          "id": "0652901d-101b-4e90-8d43-8d58ebeac796"
        },
        {
          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "### What Git actually “ignores”\n\n**`.gitignore` (and other ignore sources) mainly affect *untracked* files.**  \nIf a path is **not** in the index, Git can treat it as **ignored** when it matches an ignore pattern. Those paths won’t show up as normal untracked files in `git status` (they show as ignored when you use the right flags / porcelain lines).\n\n### I’m **not** saying “every path listed in `.gitignore` is ignored in all cases”\n\nImportant exceptions:\n\n1. **Already tracked**  \n   If a file was **committed** (or otherwise added to the index) **before** it was ignored, Git **keeps tracking it**. Adding `.env` to `.gitignore` does **not** stop tracking; it only stops *new* untracked copies from being picked up casually. You must **`git rm --cached`** (and commit) to stop tracking without deleting the working copy.\n\n2. **Negated rules**  \n   Patterns like `!important.log` can **un-ignore** paths that a broader rule would ignore.\n\n3. **Other ignore layers**  \n   Besides `.gitignore`, Git uses **`.git/info/exclude`** (local, not committed) and **global excludes** (`core.excludesFile`). Behavior is “ignore if any applicable rule says ignore,” subject to negation and specificity.\n\n4. **Forcing adds**  \n   `git add -f` can add paths that would otherwise be ignored.\n\nSo: **Git does not “ignore all files that appear in `.gitignore`” as a blanket statement** — it applies those rules under Git’s precedence and with the **tracked vs untracked** distinction.\n\n### How this ties to git-ai (checkpoint / status)\n\ngit-ai’s checkpoint path uses **`git status --porcelain=v2`** and skips entries it parses as **ignored** (`EntryKind::Ignored`). That matches **Git’s** classification for those status lines — which, again, is **not** the same as “every pattern line in `.gitignore` applied to every path regardless of tracking.”\n\n**Bottom line:** Untracked paths that Git classifies as ignored are skipped; **tracked** secrets (e.g. a committed `.env`) are **not** magically ignored by `.gitignore` alone.",
