          "text": "Yes. **git-ai treats `node_modules` as ignored for its own logic** via built-in patterns, not by reading `.gitignore`.\n\nFrom `DEFAULT_IGNORE_PATTERNS` in `git-ai/src/authorship/ignore.rs`:\n\n```6:27:/Users/Andrew/School/ReSeSS_Research/tool_testing/git-ai/src/authorship/ignore.rs\nconst DEFAULT_IGNORE_PATTERNS: &[&str] = &[\n    \"*.lock\",\n    \"Cargo.lock\",\n    // ... other patterns ...\n    \"**/node_modules/**\",\n    \"**/__snapshots__/**\",\n    // ...\n];\n```\n\nThose patterns are merged in `effective_ignore_patterns()`, which checkpoint uses to build the `IgnoreMatcher` and **skip** matching paths (e.g. `should_ignore_file_with_matcher` in `get_status_of_files` / `get_all_tracked_files`).\n\n**Caveats (same idea as before):**\n\n- This is **git-ai’s filter** for attribution/checkpoint-style processing, not `git rm`.\n- If something under `node_modules` were **tracked** in Git, Git would not report it as “ignored” like an untracked ignored file; the built-in `**/node_modules/**` pattern is still meant to filter those paths in git-ai’s matcher when paths are considered by path string.\n\nSo for normal setups where `node_modules` is untracked and in `.gitignore`, you get **both** Git treating it as ignored (where applicable) **and** git-ai’s explicit `**/node_modules/**` skip.",
