          "text": "Now I have a thorough understanding of the system. Here's what's happening:\n\n## How git-ai's git wrapper hooks get installed\n\n**Hooks are installed by running `git-ai install-hooks --dry-run=false`** — they are not installed automatically per-directory. The `install-hooks` command does two things globally:\n\n1. **`~/.cursor/hooks.json`** — registers `preToolUse` / `postToolUse` hooks that call `git-ai checkpoint cursor --hook-input stdin` for every Cursor AI tool use. This is system-wide.\n\n2. **`~/Library/Application Support/Cursor/User/settings.json`** (user-level) — sets `\"git.path\"` to the git shim at `~/.git-ai/bin/git`. This shim intercepts all git commands so git-ai can track them. Also system-wide.\n\nThe hooks are **not per-directory or per-repository** — once installed, they should apply everywhere.\n\n## Why it might work in one directory but not another\n\nThe most common cause is a **workspace-level `settings.json` override**. Cursor/VSCode's settings have a precedence hierarchy:\n\n```\nWorkspace settings (.vscode/settings.json)  ← wins\n  > User settings (~/Library/Application Support/Cursor/User/settings.json)\n```\n\nIf the other directory has a `.vscode/settings.json` or `.cursor/settings.json` that sets `\"git.path\"` to the real system git (or any other value), it overrides the user-level git-ai shim. To check:",
